a = 5
increment(a)
print(a)  # Output: 5
```

2. Pass-by-Reference: In pass-by-reference, a reference or the memory address of the argument is passed to the function. This means that any changes made to the argument within the function will affect the original variable outside the function. The original variable is directly modified. This is used in languages like C++ and some versions of Basic.

Example in C++:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

